0.title: Overview
0.body:
FORTRESS ASSAULT RULESET

OVERVIEW:
Welcome to Fortress Assault, a strategy map to guide some interesting team-based experiences around TF2

Your goal is to capture the enemy's headquarters. To do this you'll need to battle across the boardspace, fighting in each individual map as you go. You have many tools at your disposal to do so, including building attack & defend squads, upgrading those squads and completing research to further expand your capabilities.

    OBJECTIVE: Capture the enemies Headquarters 
    building
    -Use the boot camp structure to recruit new     
    attack squads
    -Build a research lab to see how to upgrade 
    your abilities

3.title: Tiles
3.body:
Tiles are the spaces on the game board. Each tile represents a TF2 map. Some maps have multiple gamemodes. These maps must be upgraded to access theit other counterparts. ARENA gamemodes are always neutral and cannot be captured. They can however have an attack squad posted on them in a defensive manner. 

BASES: Bases are the tiles that are owned. Basic bases have a garrison of 6 mercenaries for a defensive squad. Bases can be upgraded to FORTRESSES which can support 1 BUILDING, and a defensive squad of 9 mercenaries. Bases exist whenever tile ownership is officially handed over to a team. Some tiles will require a build cost for these to exist. In all cases if you take over an enemy base, you have acquired the base. NOTE: Any squad can build a base, but to upgrade to a Fortress or add a building, an engineer is required.

FORTRESSES: Fortresses are upgraded from basic bases. They have a garrison of 9 mercenaries and have 1 BUILDING SLOT. If a a Fortress is lost to an enemy team, it and the building are destroyed. 

BUILDINGS: Buildings are constructed on existing FORTRESSES. Buildings perform specific tasks. 
    -Barracks: Add +3 to garrison size. This is the
    only way to get a defense squad to full size.
    These buildings are also used to re-equip
    existing squads.
    -Boot Camp: Used to recruit new attack squads
    -Research Lab: Used to unlock upgrades and new
    buidlings. 
    -Headquarters: Special Building which functions as
    a barracks, as well as a spawn point for field 
    units. Losing this building loses the game.

2.title: Battles
2.body:
BATTLES: Battles occur whenever two enemy squads occupy the same tile. Battles take place on the gamemode type of the current map. There are several battle types.

NEUTRAL BATTLES: Occur when two opposing attack squads engage in battle over a non-owned, neutral tile. 

PRE-BATTLES: These Battles Occur when an Attack Squad Engages an enemy base that has an attack Squad Garrisoned Within. This will use the middle or lower tier version of the map, when available. In order for the enemy team to secure the tile, the enemy team must destroy the attack squad AND engage the defesnse squad (They can retreat after engaging the attack squad if they want) The PRE-BATTLE always uses the garrisoned attack squad.

ATTACK BATTLES: These are more normal battles that happen when an attack squad assaults an owned tile.

1.title: Units
1.body:
SQUADS:

Squads are the bread and butter of Fortress Assault & do the actual fighting in Fortress Assault. All squads start out with a maximum of 6 mercenaries. They are divided into two types: Attack & Defense.

ATTACK SQUADS: These squads are the only ones to move freely around the map, and thusly are the ones to attack enemy bases & fortresses.
    RECRUITING ATTACK SQUADS: Attack squads are
    always recruited fromt the BOOT CAMP     
    building. After paying the cost, use your build 
    board to assemble a stack of mercs for attack 
    squads. Mind that the cap is 6 mercs
    NOTE: Keep an eye on your research board to 
    expand the potential members and size of your
    attack squads!

DEFENSE SQUADS: These squads are the squads used  to square up the defenses of your Bases & Fortresses. They are automatically recruited when a new base is constructed or acquired. Due to Mann company regulations, these squads are provided free of charge, and are configured right before a battle. They are also confined to each base Like Attack Squads, you will only have certain classes available for this squad: Demoman, Heavy, Engineer.
    UPGRADING SQUAD SIZE: Upgrades go into   
    effect when bases are upgraded. 
        -Default Bases provide defense squads 6 
        mercenaries
        -Fortresses provide 9 Mercenaries
        -Fortresses with Barracks built have 12 
        mercenaries (NOTE: HQ Also Provides +3 
    Mercs, when assaulting the enemy HQ location, 
    the defenders will always have the maximum 
    squad size of 12)


FIELD UNITS: Field units are used to accomplish specific tasks on the board. Field units move just like other units. Field units can complete their tasks at any time during their turn. 
    -Engineers: Are the only units that can place 
    and construct buildings. Buildings are built 
    instantly. Engineers are recruited from the HQ 
    building

MOVEMENT: All units move at the same rate: each unit may move one tile per turn, there is no current way to upgrade this.

4.title: Scrap($)
4.body:
MONEY

You'll need it to fund the conquering spree you intend to go on. Money, or Scrap, is represented by the in game dollar object. There are many ways to earn and spend money.

NOTE: For general ease of use, the scrap dollar actually represents 10 dollars. This is to make transactions easier.

REVENUE SOURCES:
    -HQ = All HQ provide 150 scrap per turn
    -Bases = All Built Bases provide 20 scrap per turn
    -Gravel Quarries = Build some of these to     
    provide 150 scrap per quarry, per turn. 
    -Victory in Battle: Secure a Victorious battle and
    you will earn some Scrap as well.
        -ARENA                 = 100 scr
        -KOTH                   = 200 scr
        -ATTACK/DEFEND  = 300 scr
        -CONTROL POINT   = 500 scr
        -PAYLOAD             = 600 scr

5.title: Research
5.body:
RESEARCH is available once you construct a Lab Building. Pull the board out of your research bag and shuffle the deck. Deal out three cards.

To research something, pay the associated research cost in scrap. Upon succesful research you get one free version of that building, provided you have an engineer on the tile where you want to build it. 

Once a research has been removed from the board, reshuffle and draw a new card to replace it.

ContainedObjects.Name: BlockSquare
ContainedObjects.Description:
Automatically re-stacks any attempt at stacking. Useful when you're annoyed by objects not stacking properly!

Made by Red Mushroom. v1.0
ContainedObjects.LuaScript:
--[[
  Created by Red Mushroom
  http://steamcommunity.com/id/Red_Mush/
  Version 1.0
  MIT License
]]

local enabled = true

-- [[ UTILITY FUNCTIONS ]]

local function isStack(obj)
  return obj.getQuantity() != -1
end

local function getProto(obj)
  return obj.getCustomObject()
end

local function areProtosIdentical(protoA, protoB)
  if (not protoA) and (not protoB) then return true end -- both nil
  if (not protoA) or (not protoB) then return false end -- one is nil
  return protoA.mesh == protoB.mesh
    and protoA.diffuse == protoB.diffuse
end

local function areCompatible(objA, objB)
  local protoA = getProto(objA)
  local protoB = getProto(objB)
  return areProtosIdentical(protoA, protoB)
end

local function printTable(tbl)
  for k,v in pairs(tbl) do
    print(k, ' = ', v)
  end
end

local function isInRange(cur, min, max)
  return (cur >= min) and (cur <= max)
end

local function intersectsAxis(boxA, boxB, axis, frac)
  local posA = boxA.center[axis]
  local sizeA = boxA.size[axis] * frac / 2
  local minA = posA - sizeA
  local maxA = posA + sizeA

  local posB = boxB.center[axis]
  local sizeB = boxA.size[axis] * frac / 2
  local minB = posB - sizeB
  local maxB = posB + sizeB

  return ((minA >= minB) and (minA <= maxB))
    or ((maxA >= minB) and (maxA <= maxB))
end

local function findObjectsBelow(baseObj, radius, height)
  if not baseObj then return {} end
  radius = radius or 1
  height = height or 3

  local basePos = baseObj.getPosition()
  local baseBox = baseObj.getBoundsNormalized()

  local candidateObjs = getAllObjects()
  local results = {}

  for k, candidateObj in pairs(candidateObjs) do
    local candidatePos = candidateObj.getPosition()
    local candidateBox = candidateObj.getBoundsNormalized()

    -- Make sure we're not checking ourselves
    if not (candidateObj.getGUID() == baseObj.getGUID()) then
      -- Make sure candidate is BELOW the dropped object
      if candidatePos.y < basePos.y then
        -- Check if the bounding boxes interject on the X or Z axis
        if intersectsAxis(baseBox, candidateBox, 'x', 0.7)
        and intersectsAxis(baseBox, candidateBox, 'z', 0.7) then
          -- Store the candidate
          table.insert(results, candidateObj)
        end
      end
    end
  end

  return results
end

local function setEnabled(flag)
  enabled = flag
  local color = enabled and {r=0,g=1,b=0} or {r=1,g=0,b=0}
  broadcastToAll("Stack-O-Tron is now " .. (enabled and 'enabled' or 'disabled') .. '.', color)
  self.setColorTint(color)
end

-- [[ EVENTS ]]

function onLoad()
  setEnabled(true)
end

function onObjectRandomize(object, player_color)
  if object.getGUID() == self.getGUID() then
    setEnabled(not enabled)
  end
end

function onObjectDropped(player_color, dropped_object)
  if not enabled then return end
  local proto = getProto(dropped_object)
  local objsBelow = findObjectsBelow(dropped_object, 2.0, 5)

  for k, objBelow in pairs(objsBelow) do
    if areCompatible(objBelow, dropped_object) then
      local curPos = dropped_object.getPosition()
      local posBelow = objBelow.getPosition()
      dropped_object.setPosition({
        x = posBelow.x,
        y = curPos.y,
        z = posBelow.z,
      })
      dropped_object.setRotation(objBelow.getRotation())
      dropped_object.setVelocity({ x = 0, y = 0, z = 0 })
    end
  end
end
